    <p>Mes­sage In The Moon­cake</p>
    <p>Dur­ing the Yuan dy­nasty, moon­cakes were used by the Chi­nese to plan a re­bel­lion against the Mon­gol gov­ern­ment. Dur­ing the Mid-Au­tumn Fes­ti­val, rebels dis­trib­uted moon­cakes con­tain­ing se­cret mes­sages as the Mon­gols did not like the sweet treat. Find out if the re­bel­lion was suc­cess­ful in this sto­ry­telling ses­sion by Gate­way The­atre, which pro­motes made-in-Singapore works and tal­ent.</p>
    <p>WHERE: Sis­tic Live Stream</p>
    <p>WHEN: To­mor­row, 11am</p>
    <p>AD­MIS­SION: Free with reg­is­tra­tion INFO: www.sis­tic.com.sg/ events/kid­sclub0620p</p>
    <p>Small Big Dream­ers At Home</p>
    <p>In Na­tional Gallery Singapore’s bian­nual chil­dren’s fes­ti­val, which has moved on­line this year, kids can learn about artists and their work, cre­ate their own art­works with the in­struc­tional videos and watch live per­for­mances. The fes­ti­val has been shortliste­d for Bri­tish or­gan­i­sa­tion Kids in Mu­se­ums’ Fam­ily Friendly Mu­seum Award From Home in the Best In­ter­na­tional Dig­i­tal Ac­tiv­ity cat­e­gory, which recog­nises out­stand­ing ef­forts by mu­se­ums to en­gage and sup­port chil­dren and fam­i­lies dur­ing the pan­demic. WHERE: www.na­tion­al­gallery.sg/ small­big­dream­ers WHEN: Till Dec 27 AD­MIS­SION: Free</p>


